Gloss Comments: the bows are made shorter for warfare than for shooting fish or game. 3–4 feet for the one, 5–6 feet for shooting game. thick in the middle part only. one inch. It takes a raw buckskin hide to make the string for it, then they twisted them, when dry tho roughly!, into a cord. Oiled them once in a while. Made of buffaloribs too. The woods serving to make the short ones were mulberry, red cedar and black locust. To make the long ones, smooth bark hickory (324) was mostly used, one sapling split making two of them. The longer arows were 3'; the shorter, for the shorter bows, were about 2 feet long; they had a spear of flint or steel. Now they use spikes made by the blacksmith, hollow inside. Good arrows, with blunt heads. Material from which arrows were made: dogwood, hickory wood for blunt arrows. Hardened by holding the arrows 3 mos.) (? hard to read) over or near the fire. Dogwood winks in the water, also hickory.
